Denied’ means not admitted as citizens, or disqualified absolutely from voting or holding office; who are restricted from voting by virtue of their race, colour or membership of a particular class, place they come from [which is the focus of this story], or because of the non-payment of rents or rates’.

This study is focused on this ‘place’ restriction. It illustrates the denial of citizenship to the people of the rural areas of Guinea Bissau on the grounds of their rural origins. It is more concerned with the uncut history of their citizenship denial through the ways they are treated by the state of the nation. It delves into the description of the historical roots of how this discrimination against the rural populace became institutionalised in the ideas and practices of elections for local government, the only electoral institutions by which the people of the rural sector could choose their representatives.

This narrative hereby identifies the Law on Local Government Elections of 2006, and more significantly the Action Plan drawn up in 2005 by the Election Institute of Guinea Bissau under the auspices of the United Nations (2005-2006) to guide the election process by modifying article 5(1), 6, 10 and 24 of the 1996 Constitution.
